data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use AreEqual for exact counts — shows expected vs actual on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Use IsTrue with LINQ, but prefer CollectionAssert when possible
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use IsNotNull instead of IsTrue(x != null)
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}

```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | You already check for 3, so `> 0` is redundant |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows "expected 3, got 5" on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` | Clearer intent and message |

**Other `CollectionAssert` methods worth knowing:**

```csharp
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);       // same order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);  // any order
```

The general rule: use the **most specific assertion** available — it gives better failure messages and communicates intent more clearly.
